g.text: Nickel (Orttung & Reisser, 2014; Stephenson & Agnew, 2016). As shipping will likely contribute a minor share
of the total Arctic aerosol emissions by midcentury (Browse et al., 2013), BC from such coastal sources may
counteract the cooling effect from enhanced clouds. Furthermore, planned global limits on ships
emissions after 2020 (IMO, 2018) will reduce aerosol cooling from shipping in much the same way that air
quality improvements since the 1970s have unmasked GHG warming in urban areas. In this way, the net
climatic impact of Arctic shipping will ultimately depend on international regulatory and trade agreements
in addition to marine access. Our results thus highlight a need for integrated analysis of climatic and transport
systems to further clarify the reciprocal relationship of climate and human activities in the Arctic.
